<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: 2 LAWMAKERS PUSH LAW TO CRACK DOWN ON GANGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two lawmakers entered gang turf in Artesia Friday to promote legislation that 
would make gang members subject to more prosecution under federal law. 
</P>
<P>
Legislation introduced Thursday by Rep. Esteban E. Torres (D-La Puente) would 
allow more juvenile gang members to be tried as adults in federal courts for 
crimes such as assaults, shootings and car thefts. 
</P>
<P>
The proposed law would also mean that a youth could be tried in federal court 
for belonging to a gang whose members have committed crimes. 
</P>
<P>
At the same podium, state Sen. Cecil N. Green (D-Norwalk) plugged his proposed 
bill to increase penalties for possession of methamphetamines and PCP. The 
lawmakers said the news conference symbolized the importance of a team approach 
to the gang problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
