<HEADLINE>
<P>
LITHUANIA'S STRUGGLE FOR INDEPENDENCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As one of the participants in the April 11 White House conference with 
Baltic-American leaders, my impressions were somewhat different from those 
conveyed by your story of April 12 (Part A). 
</P>
<P>
The meeting itself was a signal that the Bush Administration is seriously 
considering various options that go beyond present rhetoric in responding to 
Soviet escalation of the Baltic situation. 
</P>
<P>
The fact that Secretary of State James Baker, National Security Adviser Brent 
Scowcroft and White House Chief of Staff John Sununu attended the meeting along 
with President Bush helped emphasize this. The further fact that a meeting 
which was scheduled to last half an hour continued for more than an hour 
indicated that the proposals which were made were not dismissed out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
No one in the Baltic delegation expected President Bush to announce a major 
policy shift based on our discussions. What we hoped for and received was the 
President's unequivocal endorsement of the right of the people of Estonia, 
Latvia and Lithuania for self-determination. We also received an invitation to 
continue providing input into the Administration's Baltic policy 
decision-making process. 
</P>
<P>
JAAK TREIMAN 
</P>
<P>
Canoga Park 
</P>
</TEXT>
