<HEADLINE>
<P>
BLACK WRITERS OF SOAPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I take exception to George Blaine Jr.'s April 7 letter concerning finding black 
writers for the NBC soap "Generations." Blaine seems to assume this should be 
easy. 
</P>
<P>
"Call the Writers Guild," he suggests. 
</P>
<P>
That's the problem. Call the Writers Guild and they will tell you -- there are 
no black writers in daytime TV. 
</P>
<P>
When "Generations" became the first soap to establish a central black family, 
head writer Sally Sussman felt it was essential to include black writers on her 
staff. Finding them wasn't easy. Even experienced writers have trouble adapting 
to soaps. It's unlike writing for anything else, and it's relentless. Writers 
turn out five scripts a week -- 52 weeks a year. The scripts are 90% dialogue, 
and they require working from another writer's outline -- a major adjustment 
for any writer. 
</P>
<P>
"Generations" is lucky enough to have two terrific black writers. Hopefully 
there will be more. 
</P>
<P>
Most importantly, the group at NBC Productions has made every effort to provide 
jobs for blacks in every field. Just this year, under the aegis of the Writers 
Guild of America, "Generations" established a minority writers program to 
create more opportunities for black writers, addressing just this problem. And 
this month NBC, in association with the National Negro College Fund, instituted 
the "Generations" Scholarship, for young blacks interested in pursuing a career 
in the arts. 
</P>
<P>
MEG BENNETT 
</P>
<P>
Writer, "Generations" 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
