<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND AT AFI FESTIVAL; 
</P>
<P>
SATURDAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Michael Wilmington 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following are The Times' recommendations for today's and Sunday's schedule of 
the American Film Institute Los Angeles International Film Festival, with 
commentary by the film reviewing staff. Information: (213) 480-3232 or (213) 
520-2000. 
</P>
<P>
Recommended: 
</P>
<P>
"A BETTER TOMORROW: THE TRILOGY "(Hong Kong, 1986; Directors: John Woo, Tsui 
Hark; Cineplex Odeon Century Plaza, 4:30, 9 and 11:15 p.m.). A slam-bang 
contemporary Hong Kong action trilogy -- about brothers on opposite sides of 
the law, and a swaggering buddy (flirtatious Chow Yunn-fatt), warring with 
various bands of vile gangsters. Coincidences and mass carnage abound. Part I 
pops with energy, light satire and full-blown emotionalism. The unrecommended 
Part II is thin, brutal, conventionally shot. The unscreened Part III -- with 
producer Tsui Hark ("Peking Opera Blues" taking over direction -- might be the 
best of the bunch. (Michael Wilmington) 
</P>
</TEXT>
