<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND AT AFI FESTIVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Michael Wilmington 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following are The Times' recommendations for today's and Sunday's schedule of 
the American Film Institute Los Angeles International Film Festival, with 
commentary by the film reviewing staff. 
</P>
<P>
Information: (213) 480-3232 or (213) 520-2000. 
</P>
<P>
SATURDAY 
</P>
<P>
Highly recommended: 
</P>
<P>
"THE NATURAL HISTORY OF PARKING LOTS"(U.S., 1990; Director: Everett Lewis; AFI 
Mark Goodson, 9 p.m.). The horror stories of privileged throw-away kids, 
considered disposable by new stepparents, gave writer/director Lewis the spine 
of his story. From these, he's created a breathtaking breakthrough film, made 
with the urgency one finds in works of the French New Wave. This one has 
poetry, irony, compassion, eroticism, beauty, a Bresson-like purity, excellent 
acting and slyly great music. (Sheila Benson) 
</P>
</TEXT>
