<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHAMIR SEEKS LIKUD GOVERNMENT BUT WON'T RULE OUT A LABOR ROLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JERUSALEM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Caretaker Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said he is trying to assemble a 
narrowly based government controlled by his hard-line Likud Party, but he 
declined Friday to rule out another coalition with the rival Labor Party. 
</P>
<P>
Shamir, who was given the task of forming Israel's next government by President 
Chaim Herzog on Friday, immediately ran into trouble. 
</P>
<P>
Yigal Bibi, a legislator of the National Religious Party, said he will back 
Likud only if the center-left Labor Party joins the coalition. The surprise 
statement brought the two major parties back to a 60-60 deadlock in the 
120-seat Knesset (Parliament). 
</P>
<P>
Herzog had turned to Shamir after Shimon Peres, the Labor leader, announced 
Thursday he had failed to assemble a coalition after 35 days of effort. 
</P>
<P>
Shamir, 74, head of the interim government, said he hopes to obtain a majority 
within the next three weeks, as required by the presidential mandate. Speaking 
to reporters, Shamir said prospects for a new Likud-Labor coalition "at the 
moment look unrealistic." 
</P>
<P>
"I would never rule out the possibility" of a coalition with Labor, he said, 
"but my efforts in this period won't be aimed at a national unity government." 
</P>
<P>
Likud and Labor ruled for 15 months in an uneasy partnership before their 
government was brought down March 15 by a Knesset vote of no confidence. 
</P>
<P>
The crisis was prompted by Shamir's refusal to accept, as Labor demanded, a 
U.S. formula for arranging Israeli-Palestinian talks. 
</P>
<P>
Herzog urged Shamir to act quickly to form a government. 
</P>
<P>
"These days, the country is in a state of political and public confusion such 
as it has never known since its founding," the president said. "There is a 
heavy and true sense of depression in the public." 
</P>
<P>
Shamir hopes to lure three right-wing factions and three ultra-Orthodox parties 
into a majority coalition in the Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, Yitzhak Shamir in Jerusalem. Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
