<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
CLU RELIEVERS WASTE CLARK'S STRONG EFFORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cal Lutheran blew a 4-0 lead en route to a 7-4 loss to Biola in a nonconference 
NAIA District 3 baseball game Friday at Biola. 
</P>
<P>
Leading, 4-0, after seven innings, Cal Lutheran (23-11, 10-7 in district play) 
pulled starting pitcher Mike Clark because of an 85-pitch limit imposed by the 
coaches. 
</P>
<P>
Clark entered the game with 22 consecutive shutout innings and a 3-0 record 
against Biola. 
</P>
<P>
He allowed only four hits and did not walk a batter. 
</P>
<P>
However, three relief pitchers could not protect the lead. 
</P>
<P>
Cal Lutheran's Peter Washington was three for five with a solo home run in the 
seventh inning. Bob Keller had two doubles and three runs batted in to lead 
Biola (13-27, 4-16). 
</P>
<P>
In order to earn a playoff berth, the Kingsmen need to win one of their next 
three District 3 games. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
SOFTBALL 
</P>
<P>
Moorpark 10, Santa Monica 0 -- After losing a Western State Conference game at 
home for the first time in seven years on Wednesday, Moorpark bounced back 
against visiting Santa Monica in a game shortened to five innings because of 
the mercy rule. 
</P>
<P>
The win gave Moorpark (25-9, 12-1) a share of its fourth consecutive conference 
title and its sixth in the past seven years. 
</P>
<P>
Freshman right-hander Robin Thomas (23-6) limited Santa Monica (5-7 in 
conference play) to four hits and struck out four. 
</P>
<P>
Catcher Missy Cress hit her third home run, a three-run shot, in Moorpark's 
five-run fourth inning. 
</P>
<P>
Canyons 5, Pierce 1 -- For the second time this week, Canyons held a WSC 
opponent to one hit. 
</P>
<P>
Michelle Ruffner threw a one-hitter Wednesday, and freshman right-hander 
Rebecca Schuster held visiting Pierce to a double in the fourth inning. 
</P>
<P>
Schuster (3-1) struck out three and walked two. 
</P>
<P>
Jill Greenwood, Debbie Rendall, Kelly Kepplinger, Debbie Barnard and Roxana 
Marta all had two hits for Canyons (20-19, 5-8). 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
SWIMMING 
</P>
<P>
Western State Conference meet -- The Ventura women are in the lead and the 
Ventura men are in second place after the second day of the three-day 
competition at Valley College. 
</P>
<P>
Ventura won the men's 200 medley relay and the women's 400 freestyle relay. 
</P>
<P>
The Valley women are in third and the men in fourth after combining for three 
individual victories on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Valley's Ashley Watier won the 50-yard backstroke and teammate Krickett Jones 
won the three-meter and one-meter diving events. 
</P>
<P>
Bill Fox of Valley was victorious on the one-meter board. 
</P>
<P>
Stuart Blair won the 100 butterfly for Canyons, but the Cougars' men's and 
women's teams are both in fifth. The Pierce men and women hold down last place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
