<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON CAMPUS: CAL STATE NORTHRIDGE; 
</P>
<P>
18 STUDENTS DESIGNING MARS PROBE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by campus correspondents and Times staff. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Eighteen Cal State Northridge seniors are aiming high and designing a 
first-of-its-kind space probe that may someday help scientists analyze the 
atmosphere of Mars. 
</P>
<P>
The students' Project Ares, in conjunction with the University Space Research 
Assn. and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, is a three-year 
effort to design a craft capable of sustained flight in the Martian atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
Project Director Neil Rubin, senior engineering major, said the purpose of the 
probe is to enable scientists to conduct a detailed survey of Mars in 
preparation for a possible visit to the planet by astronauts. 
</P>
<P>
When complete, the probe will resemble a sleek, lightweight plane with a 
40-foot wingspan. The probe will be powered by lightweight batteries and 
wing-mounted solar panels. A specially designed propeller will pull the plane 
through the thin, carbon dioxide Martian atmosphere. The collapsible craft is 
to be lifted into orbit by a Titan missile. 
</P>
<P>
The students' design and testing work is reviewed by NASA engineers. 
</P>
<P>
The faculty members heading the project are Melvin Epstein, a professor of 
mechanical engineering, and Timothy Fox, who chairs the CSUN mechanical 
engineering department. 
</P>
<P>
The project, which only seniors are eligible to work on, will be continued by a 
new group of students each fall semester. 
</P>
</TEXT>
